source_spanish_name: Programa Mundial de Alimentos
image_caption: State of Palestine, Gaza, 10 May 2018. With rampant poverty and unemployment, food insecurity is on the rise in Gaza making uninterrupted food assistance critical to protect the livelihoods of vulnerable Palestinians. Gaza is plunged into a spiral of de-development. All socio-economic indicators and humanitarian conditions continue to deteriorate. The UN foresees that Gaza will be “unliveable” by 2020. WFP assisted people struggle to ends meet with less than US$1 a day per capita. They are increasingly resorting to negative coping strategies in the face of increased hardships. Most rely on debt and support from friends and relatives, eat less or have withdrawn their children from school as they can’t afford transportation costs. WFP provides poor and food insecure families in Gaza with electronic food vouchers which give them access to local products such as eggs and yoghurt in 83 selected retail shops.
headline_summary: As WFP prioritises its operations based on available funds, 27,000 people in the West Bank stand to receive no further aid while the rest are set to receive only 80 percent of their monthly entitlement.
headline_title: Funding crunch forces WFP to cut food aid in Palestine despite rising need
